9.    Let’s say two images in different namespaces — can they speak to each other?
        Yes, they can — but it depends on the type of “namespace” you mean and the networking rules in place.

        Yes, containers/pods in different namespaces can communicate. In Kubernetes, communication is allowed by default unless restricted by NetworkPolicies.

        In Docker, containers must be on the same network to communicate. So it depends on the networking configuration and isolation rules.

        1. If you mean Kubernetes Namespaces
                ✅ By default: YES, they can communicate

                In Kubernetes:

                Pods in different namespaces can talk to each other

                As long as:

                They know the service/pod IP or DNS name

                No NetworkPolicy is blocking traffic

                Example

                A pod in namespace frontend can call a service in backend like:

                http://backend-service.backend.svc.cluster.local
                ❌ When communication is blocked

                If Network Policies are applied:

                Traffic can be restricted between namespaces

                Then communication must be explicitly allowed

                2. If you mean Docker Namespaces / Containers

                In Docker:

                Case 1: Same Docker Network

                ✔ Containers can communicate using container names

                Case 2: Different Networks

                ✖ Containers cannot communicate directly

                You must:

                Connect them to the same network OR

                Expose ports

                3. If you mean Linux Namespaces (low-level)

                Linux namespaces isolate:

                Network

                Process IDs

                File systems

                ✔ Communication is possible only if networking is configured
                (e.g., bridge, veth pairs)
