Use of -it in Docker?
    The -it flag in Docker is actually two flags combined:
        -it = -i + -t
    🔹 1. -i → Interactive mode
            Keeps STDIN (input) open
            Allows you to type input into the container

        👉 Without -i, you can’t send input (keyboard won’t work)

    🔹 2. -t → Terminal (TTY)
        Allocates a pseudo-terminal
        Gives you a nice shell interface (like a real Linux terminal)

        👉 Without -t, output looks messy and no proper prompt

    🔹 Together: -it
            Enables interactive terminal session
            Lets you run and interact with shell inside container

    Example:
        docker run -it python

        Opens Python interactive shell:
            >>>

        🔹 When to Use -it

    Use it when:

        You want to debug inside container
        You need a shell (bash/sh)
        Running interactive apps (Python REPL, CLI tools)
        🔹 When NOT to Use

                Don’t use -it when:

                    Running background services (like APIs, servers)

        Example:

            docker run -d nginx

        🔹 Interview Answer (Short)

            "-it in Docker combines interactive input (-i) and a terminal (-t), allowing users to run and interact with a container shell in real time."
