KEDA —> Kubernetes Event Driven Autoscaling

HPA is great. But it only scales on CPU and memory.

What if your Kafka consumer has 1 million messages waiting  but CPU is at 5%?

HPA sees no reason to scale. Your queue keeps growing. Users wait.
KEDA fixes this.

─────────────────────────
What is KEDA?

Kubernetes Event Driven Autoscaler.

It extends HPA to scale on any external metric or event source like  Kafka lag, SQS depth, Prometheus metrics, cron schedules, HTTP traffic.

And it can scale all the way to zero then back up the moment events arrive.

─────────────────────────
How it works:
1️⃣ You create a ScaledObject —> define what to watch
2️⃣ KEDA polls the source —> checks queue depth, message count, schedule 3️⃣ KEDA feeds HPA with custom metrics
4️⃣ HPA scales the workload based on event-driven values
5️⃣ Queue drains → pods scale back to zero

─────────────────────────
60+ built-in scalers:
→ Kafka ( scale consumers based on topic lag. 1 pod per N messages.)

→ AWS SQS (scale based on queue depth. More messages = more workers.)

→ Prometheus  (scale on any custom metric. Error rate, latency, request rate.)

→ Cron (time-based scaling. Scale up at 9am, scale to zero at 6pm.)

→ HTTP requests (scale to zero when no traffic arrives.)

─────────────────────────
HPA vs KEDA:

🟣 HPA → CPU/memory only, built-in, min 1 pod always. Use for stateless web services.

🟢 KEDA → any event/metric, extends HPA, scales to zero. Use for event-driven workloads.

─────────────────────────
KEDA doesn't replace HPA  it extends it.

Scale to zero is KEDA's biggest advantage  massive cost savings for batch and event-driven workloads.

KEDA is CNCF graduated  production ready and widely adopted.

Are you using KEDA in your cluster or still relying on HPA only? 💬
